SALMONELLOSIS, MUNG BEANS - SWEDEN (STOCKHOLM) (02): BACKGROUND
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Tue 14 Nov 2006
From: Steve Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
Source: Gideon.com [edited]
<http://www.gideononline.com>

Regarding a recent outbreak in Stockholm, Sweden reports 3500 to 5500 cases
of salmonellosis each year, rates comparable to those of other Scandinavian
countries (see graph at
<http://exhibit.gideononline.com/Salmonella-Scand.jpg>).
A chronology of notable salmonellosis outbreaks in Sweden follows (source:
Gideon
<http://www.GideonOnline.com>):
Primary references are available on request.
Notable outbreaks:
1974 - An outbreak of serotype Typhimurium infection in southeastern Sweden
was caused by contaminated cream.
1978 - An outbreak (9500 cases) of serotype Enteritidis infection among 28
schools in Stockholm was caused by contaminated mayonnaise.
1990 - An outbreak (108 cases) of serotype Enteritidis infection was
reported among physicians attending a Radiology conference in Malmo.
1999 - An outbreak (78 cases) of paratyphoid B infection was reported among
Swedish tourists to Turkey.
2001 - An outbreak of serotype Livingstone infection in Norway (44 cases)
and Sweden (16 cases) was ascribed to a Swedish fish product.
2001 - Outbreaks of serotype Typhimurium DT 104 infection caused by a batch
of imported Turkish halvah were reported in Sweden (25 cases) and Australia.
2001 - An outbreak of serotype Oranienburg due to contaminated German
chocolate affected several European countries. 18 cases were reported in
Sweden at the time.
2001 - An outbreak (303 cases, including 149 in Sweden) of serotype
Enteritidis PT 14b infection was reported among Norwegian, Finish and
Swedish tourists returning from Crete and Karpathos. The probable source
was contaminated poultry.
2002 - An outbreak (352 cases) of serotypes Enteritidis and Hadar infection
ascribed to chicken was reported among passengers on a ferry traveling
between Sweden and Poland.
2003 - An outbreak (112 cases) of serotype Typhimurium DT108 infection
caused by kebab meat imported from Denmark was reported in Blekinge.
2004 - An outbreak of serotype Thompson infection (20 cases in Norway and
13 in Sweden) was associated with contaminated ruccola salad.
2005 - An outbreak of serotype Stourbridge infection in Sweden (6 cases),
Switzerland (3), Germany (2), Austria (5), United Kingdom (3) and France
(18) was caused by unpasteurized French soft cheese.
2005 - An outbreak (178 cases) of serotype Goldcoast infection in Majorca
affected tourists from Scotland (37), Ireland (6), Sweden (6), Norway (8),
Denmark (3), Germany (20) and Finland (4).
2006 - An outbreak (13 cases) of serotype Typhimurium infection in Sweden
was caused by contaminated salami imported from Italy.
--
Dr. Steve Berger
Geographic Medicine
Tel Aviv Medical Center, Israel
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
